_embedded.description: The cottage is of stone construction under a pitched slate roof.  It retains period features such as stripped ledge and brace doors and traditional fireplaces.  There are two reception rooms, a conservatory, a fitted kitchen and a shower room on the ground floor, two bedrooms on the first floor and an attic room on the second floor.  The gardens have been landscaped and are fully enclosed.  There is off street parking for up to three cars.

The property has a wealth of character features including exposed beams, wooden floors, an inglenook fireplace and a working well.  The accommodation comprises an entrance hall, a downstairs bathroom, a sitting room, a kitchen/dining room and two first floor double bedrooms.  There is a south facing garden, a garden store with power and light and off street parking for two/three cars.

The cottage originally dates from the 1860s and is principally of stone construction under a clay tiled roof.  It has been improved and updated to include a contemporary style kitchen but retains traditional fireplaces, exposed floorboards and stripped ledge and brace doors.  The rear garden is subdivided by a driveway with undercover parking for one car and off street parking for two additional cars.

AMPTHILL – is a small Georgian market town and civil parish in Bedfordshire, between Bedford and Luton, with a population of about 7,000. A regular market has taken place on Thursdays for centuries. The town has several lively pubs, a wide variety of restaurants, a Waitrose supermarket and a selection of small independent specialist shops. A number of small businesses such as solicitors, estate agents, financial services, hairdressers and music schools are located in town. Larger businesses are to be found on the commercial and industrial developments on the outskirts, along the town’s bypass. 		*** DETACHED BUNGALOW***
INDIGO RESIDENTIAL are offering this rarely available detached bungalow set in this delightful village of Barton-Le-Clay surrounded by rolling countryside. An internal viewing of this property is highly recommended to truly appreciate the size and condition throughout.
The internal living accommodation is made up of firstly a porch area, the entrance hall leading to a lounge at the front of the property with the re fitted kitchen breakfast to the rear along with utility room. The properties living space has been further improved with the addition of a fantastic conservatory, currently used as a dining room and leading to the patio area and onto the beautifully maintained garden. 
The master bedroom is bright and airy with en-suite shower room. The family bathroom is refitted and also leads onto the second bedroom creating a Jack and Jill en-suite. Externally the home is well set back from the main road with gravel driveway offering ample car parking and detached garage. The rear garden is south facing and mainly laid to lawn with well stocked boarders, it is a respectable size in excess of 120 ft long. 
The property benefits from being double glazed and has a refitted kitchen as well as newly fitted en-suites, one to the master and one Jack and Gill bathroom to the second bedroom. 
The approx of square footage of this property is a massive 1,050 sq. ft and this home could also offer further living accommodation via an extension if required subject to planning permission being granted. 
EPC rating E

The cottage was built circa 1650 as part of the Ravensden Manor estate and was used as a public house from circa 1731 until 1929. It is of timber framed construction with colour washed brick elevations and retains several period features such as inglenook fireplaces and exposed beams.  A ground floor extension provides the study/bedroom three.  The gardens surround the cottage and extend to approximately 0.26 acres in total and there is also a driveway and single garage with a storage room.
